#### Memoization
Memoization is an optimization technique where you store the results of expensive function calls and reuse them when the same inputs occur again. This is particularly useful for recursive algorithms that solve overlapping subproblems.

**Example: Optimized Fibonacci with Memoization**

```java
import java.util.HashMap;

public class MemoizedFibonacci {
    private static HashMap<Integer, Integer> memo = new HashMap<>();

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int n = 5;
        System.out.println("Fibonacci of " + n + " is: " + fibonacci(n));
    }

    public static int fibonacci(int n) {
        // Check if result is already computed
        if (memo.containsKey(n)) {
            return memo.get(n);
        }
        // Base cases
        if (n == 0) return 0;
        if (n == 1) return 1;

        // Recursive call and store the result
        int result = fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
        memo.put(n, result);
        return result;
    }
}
```

